text: Can We Predict The Future? South Dakota Industry Trends To 2014
label: HH1

text: This article was published in the October 2006 South Dakota Labor Bulletin.
label: BODY

text: In what direction and at what growth rate are industry trends predicted? A look at which types of
label: BODY

text: industries are growing and which are not provides a synopsis of the economy as a whole. The general
label: BODY

text: outlook for South Dakota is characterized by job growth in the coming decade. Almost all industries
label: BODY

text: are estimated to see an increase in worker levels over the next ten years.
label: BODY

text: From 2004 to 2014, the total number of workers in South Dakota is projected to increase by 57,030
label: BODY

text: for a total of 499,370 workers. South Dakota's annual average percent change of 1.29 percent is
label: BODY

text: expected to be just slightly lower than the nation's 1.34 percent rate. The 2004-2014 round of South
label: BODY

text: Dakota worker projections by class of worker and industry were recently completed by the Labor
label: BODY

text: Market Information Center. Historical time-series data and state and national economic trends were
label: BODY

text: used as variables in various statistical models to project workforce levels. (General assumptions are
label: BODY

text: made that no major catastrophic events or natural disasters which would significantly affect economic
label: BODY

text: activities of these industries will occur during the projection period.)
label: BODY

text: South Dakota's workforce is comprised of different classes of workers: wage and salaried, self-
label: BODY

text: employed and unpaid family workers. Wage and salaried workers, one of the major components of
label: BODY

text: the workforce, will account for almost all of the total worker increase from 2004 to 2014. They
label: BODY

text: currently comprise about 87 percent of the total number of workers in South Dakota.
label: BODY

text: The number of self-employed agriculture workers is projected to decline during the next 10 years.
label: BODY

text: This decline is due to an ongoing shift among worker classes. For example, small farms, which are
label: BODY

text: generally run by self-employed persons, are being consolidated into larger farming operations. Many
label: BODY

text: of the larger farms' employees are then classified as wage and salaried workers. Meanwhile, the
label: BODY

text: number of nonagricultural proprietors is projected to increase. Self-employed people in this group
label: BODY

text: generally work for themselves (e.g. as independent accountants, construction contractors, lawyers,

text: As shown in the table below, all of the wage and salaried industry divisions are expected to grow
label: BODY

text: from 2004 to 2014.
label: BODY

text: Mining
label: HH1

text: The number of workers employed in the mining industry division is projected to increase by 3.9
label: BODY

text: percent over the next ten years. The expected worker gains in the mining industry will be minimal.
label: BODY

text: Advances in mining technology will slow worker growth as new machinery and processes increase
label: BODY

text: worker productivity. Environmental regulations and foreign competition will continue to play a major
label: BODY

text: role in the future of the mining industry division.
label: BODY

text: Utilities
label: HH1

text: Worker levels in the utilities industry division are projected to increase by 1.5 percent.  An increase in
label: BODY

text: the water, sewage and other systems industry is projected to more than offset a slight decline in the
label: BODY

text: natural gas distribution industry. Worker levels in the electric power generation and transmission
label: BODY

text: industry are projected to remain stable, but technology and automation are expected to decrease labor
label: BODY

text: needs in the distribution of natural gas.  Stricter regulations regarding water, sewage and the
label: BODY

text: environmental impacts of treating both are increasing the number of workers needed in the industry.
label: BODY

text: The need for new community water supplies and waste treatment facilities in growing areas of the
label: BODY

text: state will also add to the employment levels in this industry.
label: BODY

text: Construction
label: HH1

text: The construction industry division is projected to increase worker levels by 22.1 percent. All areas of
label: BODY

text: construction (buildings, heavy and civil engineering, and special trade contractors) are expected to
label: BODY

text: show gains in the number of workers.
label: BODY

text: The demand for residential homes and nonresidential buildings in certain parts of South Dakota is
label: BODY

text: predicted to be strong. The aging baby boomers will spur job growth for building contractors over the
label: BODY

text: next ten years due to the demand for specialized homes, apartments and assisted living centers.

text: Employment in specialty trades contracting, the largest segment of the industry, is expected to have
label: BODY

text: faster growth than in new home construction. Special trade contractors generally specialize in a
label: BODY

text: specific construction activity, performing only part of the work needed to finish a construction
label: BODY

text: project. These activities will become more important as many construction jobs will be subcontracts
label: BODY

text: for specialized maintenance and remodeling work such as tile, marble, cement and concrete
label: BODY

text: installation, air-conditioning and refrigeration installation and repair, and roofing. Job growth will also
label: BODY

text: occur in the heavy and civil engineering construction area. Federal highway funds designed to
label: BODY

text: improve South Dakota's highway infrastructure will increase the number of workers needed in this
label: BODY

text: area.
label: BODY

text: Manufacturing
label: HH1

text: For years, the South Dakota manufacturing industry division has created its own path, diverging from
label: BODY

text: the declining national trends. Manufacturing is expected to add 2,220 wage and salaried jobs. The
label: BODY

text: area expected to have the most job growth is the food manufacturing industry, adding 550 jobs. This
label: BODY

text: projected growth correlates with goals of South Dakota’s 2010 Initiative to promote further expansion
label: BODY

text: of value-added processing of agricultural products, such as slaughtering animals, preparing processed
label: BODY

text: meats and meat byproducts, and refining animal fat, bones and meat scraps.
label: BODY

text: The next largest area of manufacturing growth is the machinery manufacturing industry, with 540
label: BODY

text: added jobs expected. Growth is also expected for agricultural, construction and mining machinery
label: BODY

text: manufacturing industries over the next ten years.
label: BODY

text: Wholesale Trade
label: HH1

text: The number of wholesale trade workers is expected to increase by 6.9 percent over the next 10 years.
label: BODY

text: Consolidation and the spread of new technology are the main reasons job growth for this industry
label: BODY

text: division will be slower than the average for all industries. Although there is a growing trend in e-
label: BODY

text: commerce, wholesalers will still be needed for their supply and distribution services. One area
label: BODY

text: projected to grow the fastest is  drugs and druggists' sundries; this growth is related to South Dakota’s
label: BODY

text: aging population and the increasing medicinal needs of baby boomers.  The other area for which fast
label: BODY

text: growth is projected is motor vehicle and motor vehicle parts and supplies.  This division will likely be
label: BODY

text: less impacted by e-commerce than other types of wholesale trade.
label: BODY

text: Retail Trade
label: HH1

text: The retail trade industry division is expected to add 5,870 workers. Motor vehicle and parts dealers
label: BODY

text: and gasoline stations are projected to do well during the next ten years. The rise in business travel and
label: BODY

text: increased tourism activity will boost the need for travel accommodations including gas stations. Many
label: BODY

text: of these places offer a variety of convenience products and services from fast food and groceries to
label: BODY

text: shower facilities. Many retail businesses will also benefit over the next 10 years as baby boomers
label: BODY

text: retire or cut back to part-time employment and have more leisure time for enjoying things like
label: BODY

text: shopping and travel.
label: BODY

text: General merchandise, miscellaneous retailers and non-store retailers are also projected to thrive. This
label: BODY

text: industry includes used merchandise stores and "non-store" retailers. The changing attitude in
label: BODY

text: consumer shopping will allow electronic and mail order businesses to capture broader markets,
label: BODY

text: increasing the need for more workers. One-stop general retailers and specialized store retailers (office
label: BODY

text: supplies, gift stores, etc). are also projected to have strong growth.
label: BODY

text: Transportation & Warehousing
label: HH1

text: Worker levels in the transportation and warehousing industry division are projected to increase by
label: BODY

text: 14.2 percent. Job growth will be concentrated in the truck transportation industry. The demand for
label: BODY

text: trucking services is correlated with the projected growth in the manufacturing and trade industries. As
label: BODY

text: more products are produced and purchased over the Internet or other sources, the trucking industry
label: BODY

text: will need more workers to transport these goods.
label: BODY

text: Information
label: HH1

text: Worker levels in the information industry are projected to increase by 590 by 2014.  The effect of
label: BODY

text: October 2006
label: BODY

text: Page 3 of 6
label: BODY

text: South Dakota e-Labor Bulletin
label: BODY

text: rapid advancements within the communications industry will cause businesses to expand in order to
label: BODY

text: remain competitive. Companies that once specialized in just one aspect of communication, whether it
label: BODY

text: was cable television, Internet or telephone service, now offer customers a combination of services in
label: BODY

text: “package deals” and will continue to do so. Beyond this trend in telecommunications and Internet
label: BODY

text: service providers, modest growth is projected to be fairly evenly distributed among the publishing,
label: BODY

text: motion picture and video recording and broadcasting areas.
label: BODY

text: Finance & Insurance
label: HH1

text: Over the next ten years, the finance & insurance industry division is expected to increase worker
label: BODY

text: levels by 12.7 percent. Nearly three-fourths of projected job growth in the finance and insurance
label: BODY

text: division will be concentrated in the credit intermediation and related activities division. Included in
label: BODY

text: this division are businesses that extend credit in the form of credit cards and post-dated check-cashing
label: BODY

text: services. These businesses have shown tremendous growth in the previous 10 years and are expected
label: BODY

text: to continue to add workers.
label: BODY

text: Real Estate & Rental & Leasing
label: HH1

text: The real estate and rental and leasing industry division is projected to add 510 workers by 2014. A
label: BODY

text: portion of this growth will be due to increased housing needs (impacting both real estate sales and
label: BODY

text: rental/leasing) in the state’s population growth areas. The perception that real estate is a valuable
label: BODY

text: investment will also continue to positively influence worker levels in this industry. Interest rates
label: BODY

text: remaining relatively low, which is difficult to predict over a 10-year period, would also stimulate sales
label: BODY

text: of real estate and worker levels in this industry.  Also contributing to the projected growth in this
label: BODY

text: industry division will be the rental and leasing of products such as automobiles and consumer goods
label: BODY

text: such as home appliances and electronics.
label: BODY

text: Professional, Scientific & Technical Services
label: HH1

text: Worker levels in the professional, scientific and technical services industry division are projected to
label: BODY

text: increase by 25.9 percent.  The big growth leaders within this division will be management and
label: BODY

text: technical consulting services; accounting, tax preparation and payroll services; computer system
label: BODY

text: design and related services; architectural and engineering services; and other professional, scientific
label: BODY

text: and technical services. Growth in other industries means increased demand for advice in all areas of
label: BODY

text: business planning and implementation. Businesses will continue to need advice on issues ranging
label: BODY

text: from compliance with government workplace safety, environmental and tax laws to designing new
label: BODY

text: computer systems or online distribution systems. In order to cut costs, many firms are outsourcing
label: BODY

text: administrative and human resources functions like managing payroll and benefits programs to
label: BODY

text: consultants.  Globalization, too, will continue to spur growth in this industry division, as consulting
label: BODY

text: firms advise clients on strategies to expand into foreign markets.
label: BODY

text: Management of Companies & Enterprises
label: HH1

text: The management of companies and enterprises industry division is projected to add 280 workers by
label: BODY

text: 2014.  Establishments in this industry division own a controlling interest in or manage the overall
label: BODY

text: operations of other businesses.   On behalf of those businesses, the management company undertakes
label: BODY

text: the strategic or organizational planning and decision-making role of the company or enterprise.
label: BODY

text: These management firms advise on almost every aspect of corporate operations, from marketing and
label: BODY

text: finance to information systems and human resources.  Growth in this industry division can also be
label: BODY

text: attributed to the increasing complexity of these various management functions, due in part to
label: BODY

text: technology and increasingly fierce competition in a global economy.
label: BODY

text: Administrative & Support and Waste Management Services
label: HH1

text: The administrative and support and waste management services industry division is projected to have
label: BODY

text: a 23.0 percent worker increase by 2014.  The industries projected to note the largest growth are
label: BODY

text: employment services, services to buildings and dwellings, and business support services.  The
label: BODY

text: demand for temporary help and contract help in order to reduce costs is one reason for the expected
label: BODY

text: worker increase. Because of the complexity of employee-related laws, businesses are expected to
label: BODY

text: increasingly enter into relationships with professional employer organizations to handle things like
label: BODY

text: October 2006
label: BODY

label: BODY

text: health benefits, workers’ compensation claims, and tax compliance. Similarly, as a cost-saving
label: BODY

text: measure, businesses will contract with outside agencies for services to buildings such as landscaping,
label: BODY

text: grounds keeping, tree trimming and pruning, pest control, and general cleaning and maintenance
label: BODY

text: rather than employ staff for those tasks. Projected growth among establishments providing business
label: BODY

text: support services like telephone calling and answering and telemarketing is also related to businesses
label: BODY

text: looking to reduce internal costs.
label: BODY

text: Educational Services – Private
label: HH1

text: Worker levels in the private education services industry division are projected to increase by 960.
label: BODY

text: Increases will be found largely among private elementary, secondary and universities as these
label: BODY

text: establishments expand their staffs to accommodate increasing enrollments in the state’s more urban
label: BODY

text: areas. At the post-secondary level, the growing emphasis on continuing education to meet career
label: BODY

text: goals and for earning potential will be at play.  At the elementary and secondary levels, school
label: BODY

text: reforms calling for more individual attention to students will help increase employment levels.
label: BODY

text: Health care & Social Assistance
label: HH1

text: The health care and social assistance industry division is projected to be both the largest growth
label: BODY

text: industry and the fastest growth industry division over the projections period. The aging population
label: BODY

text: and advancements in medical care will help ensure continued worker growth within the health care
label: BODY

text: services industry, especially for hospitals. The continuing shift from inpatient care to outpatient
label: BODY

text: treatment will boost worker growth in health practitioner offices as well. Nursing and residential care
label: BODY

text: facilities are also expected to have strong growth due to South Dakota's growing elderly population.
label: BODY

text: While growth in the social assistance industry is not projected to be as brisk as in health care, it will
label: BODY

text: also see healthy increases in worker levels to 2014.  Increased demand for individual and family
label: BODY

text: counseling, community food and other relief services, vocational rehabilitation and child day care
label: BODY

text: services will all contribute to this growth.  Some of the projected job growth is due to the expansion
label: BODY

text: of services for the elderly and the aging baby-boom generation. Earlier and improved integration of
label: BODY

text: the physically disabled and mentally ill into society will contribute to employment growth, as will
label: BODY

text: increased demand for drug and alcohol abuse prevention programs. The growth in child day care
label: BODY

text: services reflects, in part, demographic trends; the number of children under age five is expected to
label: BODY

text: increase. There will likely be a need for childcare during extended hours, such as evenings and
label: BODY

text: weekends. For example, many workers in the growing health care industry within facilities in which
label: BODY

text: 24/7 care is inherent are parents who need care for their own children while they are at work.
label: BODY

text: Arts, Entertainment and Recreation
label: BODY

text: Worker levels in the arts, entertainment and recreation industry division are projected to increase by
label: BODY

text: 1,590. The bulk of the growth will be in the other amusement and recreation industry and in the
label: BODY

text: gambling industry. As mentioned earlier, it is expected that as more baby boomers retire, travel and
label: BODY

text: other leisure activities will increase.  This will also impact businesses like casinos, golf courses and
label: BODY

text: amusement establishments. A growing consciousness of the need for weight control and exercise will
label: BODY

text: also contribute to higher worker levels in this industry division, which includes fitness and
label: BODY

text: recreational sports centers.
label: BODY

text: Accommodation & Food Services
label: HH1

text: The accommodation and food services industry division is projected to show strong growth the next
label: BODY

text: ten years, up 5,780 workers. Again, the large number of baby boom retirees or semi-retirees with
label: BODY

text: more time for travel will increase business at places like hotels, motels, bed and breakfast inns, RV
label: BODY

text: parks and restaurants.  Population growth in the state will also help boost employment levels in these
label: BODY

text: same types of accommodation services and in all types of restaurants, ranging from fast food to full
label: BODY

text: service.
label: BODY

text: Government
label: HH1

text: The number of workers employed by government entities is projected to increase by 7.5 percent. This
label: BODY

text: includes workers employed by federal, state, local and tribal government, all of which are projected to
label: BODY

text: South Dakota e-Labor Bulletin
label: BODY

text: increase worker levels over the next ten years.
label: BODY

text: State worker growth will be concentrated in state education, with South Dakota's universities adding
label: BODY

text: workers to keep pace with the demand for post-secondary education. This includes an expected
label: BODY

text: increase in the number of college students with work study jobs.
label: BODY

text: Local governments are expected to add workers in both the education and the non-education areas.
label: BODY

text: The 2010 Initiative outlines a series of specific goals for economic growth and will help certain areas
label: BODY

text: of South Dakota see increased business growth and increased population. These growing areas of the
label: BODY

text: state will need additional local government workers as well to accommodate their additional citizens
label: BODY

text: with such publicly-provided services as utilities, street maintenance, parks and recreation programs,
label: BODY

text: etc.
label: BODY

text: Federal government job growth generated by increased homeland security needs may be offset by
label: BODY

text: projected slow growth or declines in other federal sectors due to government cost-cutting and the
label: BODY

text: growing use of private contracts.  Projecting employment levels for government is especially
label: BODY

text: challenging, since legislated changes affect spending levels and hiring decisions for government
label: BODY

text: agencies. But domestic programs are likely to see continued cuts in their budgets as Congress seeks to
label: BODY

text: reduce the federal budget deficit.  Employment declines will likely be carried out mainly through
label: BODY

text: attrition—not replacing workers who retire or leave the federal government for other reasons.
label: BODY
